I want to design a bounded local-first MERMATE inference architecture that can take any simple idea, encode it as a structured boundary-memory problem, and reconstruct a deeper hidden architecture from it using GoT-style recursive reasoning over holographic manifolds. The system should behave like a self-auditing multi-agent geometric intelligence stack, where each major reasoning function is split into bounded components that verify each other before any high-cost synthesis, architectural claim, or final inference is allowed.

The architecture starts with a boundary-intake layer that continuously ingests the initial user idea, its constraints, its implied geometry, its scale relationships, its conceptual tensions, and its hidden architectural depth. That input should be normalized into a local structured memory field rather than treated as raw text. The memory field should preserve semantic position, scale, relation, uncertainty, causal implication, and compression potential. This field becomes the boundary state from which the deeper manifold of reasoning is reconstructed.

That boundary-memory state should then be passed into a MERMATE reconstruction layer that interprets the user’s idea as a holographic inverse problem. The goal is not to answer immediately, but to infer the hidden bulk architecture that could best explain the idea across depth, scale, and coherence. The reconstruction should treat the final architecture as an emergent metric over a conceptual manifold, where the simplest viable hidden structure is inferred from observable boundary traces such as repeated motifs, contradictions, latent abstractions, missing bridges, implied objectives, and unexplored directions.

I need the system to explicitly separate the reasoning into bounded planes. These planes should include boundary intake, memory encoding, gauge selection, manifold reconstruction, expert routing, branch exploration, branch validation, merge discipline, scoring, final synthesis, and UX-state rendering. The UX may show only seven visible layers of thought, but the underlying controller should remain faithful to a bounded GoT orchestration model where all reasoning is staged, scored, and pruned rather than allowed to become an unbounded swarm.

The first agent in the system should not act like a generic responder. Its job should be to architect the run itself. It must determine what kind of idea is being processed, what hidden structure is likely present, what the likely final artifact should be, what expert roles are required, which stages are necessary, what invariants must remain fixed, what success means, what the expected token budget should be, and which model tiers should be used at each stage. The first agent should generate a reasoning architecture plan before the rest of the system begins deeper inference.

Once the run architecture is established, the system should construct a Mermaid-like graph of reasoning execution that shows how the idea will be processed through the bounded agent lattice. This graph should define which agents run first, which can run concurrently, which must wait for validation, which are candidates for pruning, which can be merged, and which model calls are cheap versus expensive. The graph should not be aesthetic only; it should reflect the actual executable reasoning order.

I want the architecture to support approximately 20 expert agents, but these agents must not behave like isolated personalities. They should act as specialized organs inside one coherent intelligence. Each agent must operate on a shared evolving architecture state that includes the original objective, shared invariants, prior branch results, current score state, provenance, and known failure traces. This prevents the common failure mode where only one agent seems to think at a time or where agents produce disconnected outputs that do not accumulate into one final intelligent result.

The system should support true concurrent inference when appropriate, but concurrency must be bounded, measurable, and meaningful. Agents should be grouped into disciplined concurrent batches only when there is a real need for exploration, expert specialization, validation diversity, or synthesis pressure. Every concurrent batch should be logged in canonical order with stage number, parent state, selected experts, model used, start time, end time, token usage, latency, validation score, and retain-or-prune outcome. The UX should clearly indicate that multiple expert channels may be active in one bounded stage, even if the display remains simple and user-friendly.

The core reconstruction layer should implement the MERMATE idea that geometry is the compressed memory of boundary relations. In practical terms, the system should define a multiscale memory field over the input idea, where each memory element tracks semantic structure, abstraction scale, directional implication, and causal relation. The system should then infer a hidden bulk manifold whose metric best explains the memory field. The inferred metric should not be treated as physical spacetime literally unless specified, but as an architectural geometry of thought where depth corresponds to abstraction, curvature corresponds to conceptual pressure, and radial structure corresponds to scale emergence.

I want the reasoning engine to treat gauge choice as a first-class problem. Before deep reconstruction, the system must determine the best coordinate language for the idea. This means choosing how depth, abstraction, relation, and causality will be represented so that the resulting manifold is not distorted by a poor coordinate frame. The gauge-selection layer should infer the simplest stable mapping from boundary scale to hidden depth, and it should log why that mapping was selected. The architecture must assume that many failure cases are not failures of reasoning but failures of representation, and it should correct for that.

The branch exploration layer should then generate multiple candidate hidden architectures from the same boundary-memory field. Some branches may emphasize mathematical structure, some physical interpretability, some engineering realizability, some UX simplicity, some speculative depth, and some cost-bounded execution. Each branch should remain tethered to the same objective. Branches should not proliferate endlessly. The controller must impose bounded branching, score intermediate outputs externally, and prune weak branches early.

The validation system should be externalized rather than self-flattering. Agents must not merely praise their own work. A router-side validation layer should score every branch according to invariant preservation, coherence with the objective, structural completeness, novelty under constraint, feasibility, depth-to-simplicity ratio, and explanatory power. Validation should also inspect whether branches are drifting into theatrical complexity without actual architectural gain. Only branches that improve the objective in measurable ways should survive.

I need the system to support optional merge behavior, but only if merge improves score and does not destroy coherence. Merge should not be automatic. The merge layer should test whether combining multiple surviving branches produces a stronger architecture than keeping one dominant path. If merge increases contradiction, latency, token waste, or conceptual blur, it should be rejected. If it increases explanatory depth, elegance, and completeness while preserving boundedness, it may be accepted and promoted to final synthesis.

The model routing policy should be explicit and cost-aware. Stronger models such as high-tier reasoning models should be used only for difficult synthesis, ambiguity resolution, hard validation, branch repair, or final convergence. Cheaper models should be used for decomposition, structural extraction, formatting, branch proposal, redundancy checks, and local repairs. The system must predict token needs before each stage, decide whether an expensive call is warranted, and leave room for large-capacity reasoning only when truly needed. This should produce a reasoning engine that can be deep when necessary, but economical by default.

I also want an inference-measurement layer that can verify the architecture over time. This layer should log every inference call, every stage transition, every branch, every validation score, every merge decision, every latency measurement, every token estimate, every actual token spend, every model assignment, and every failure trace. The system must be able to support not just a single run, but aggregate analysis across hundreds or thousands of inference calls so that it becomes clear which agents help, which agents are redundant, which stage patterns work best, which models are overused, and whether the architecture is actually becoming more intelligent over time in terms of systems thinking and final output quality.

I want a self-audit layer with around 40 checks that continuously inspect the reasoning engine during and after execution. These checks should validate objective preservation, invariant integrity, branch consistency, gauge stability, metric plausibility, concurrency correctness, model allocation discipline, latency tolerances, token budget safety, merge correctness, provenance retention, scoring sanity, UX-state honesty, failure recovery, and final-answer completeness. If the audit layer detects architectural drift, false concurrency, incoherent agent behavior, uncontrolled token spend, invalid merge, or validation collapse, it should flag the issue and either degrade, isolate, or stop the current branch before final output is generated.

The architecture should make local execution and reproducibility explicit. The reasoning controller should be capable of building a reproducible run-state artifact for each execution, where the run-state records configuration, selected experts, model policy, batch schedule, validation history, pruning history, merge history, final scores, and final synthesis. This artifact should be replayable so that a later verifier can inspect how the final output was derived without exposing raw private chain-of-thought. In this sense, the system should not merely answer; it should produce an auditable architecture-of-answer.

I want Opus, or the designated verifier model, to act as the final systems auditor. It should verify that all returns are logged in order, all stage transitions are coherent, all concurrent batches are real and not cosmetic, all scores are meaningful, all merge decisions are justified, all model allocations are appropriate, and all surviving branches genuinely improve the final result. As a stress test, Opus should first generate a deeply complex architectural problem of its own, compress it into a simple seed idea, and then observe how the system expands that seed through the 20-agent bounded GoT controller into a fully reconstructed architecture. This should test whether the engine can turn simple ideas into super-complex final structures while remaining coherent, bounded, and auditable.

The UX should remain simple even if the internal architecture is extremely deep. The user should not be overwhelmed with raw internal detail, but they should always be able to see the current reasoning layer, the active mode of thought, whether the system is exploring, validating, pruning, merging, or converging, and whether the system is using lightweight or high-tier inference. The UX should communicate honest next-state thinking without pretending that a single agent is doing all the work. It should feel like one intelligence progressing through intelligible layers.

The final design should make clear how a self-driven GoT-style MERMATE system can take a simple input, encode it as a boundary-memory problem, reconstruct a hidden manifold of thought, route expert agents across bounded inference layers, validate and prune branches, merge only when beneficial, self-audit continuously, measure its own reasoning economy, and only then produce a final high-quality answer, architecture, or transformation. The finished system should be simple on the surface, super-deep in orchestration, mathematically bounded, validator-backed, concurrency-aware, cost-aware, reproducible, and capable of turning even the simplest seed idea into a carefully verified super-complex architecture without losing coherence.